				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$4\times4$\end{document} transfer matrix of electric- and magnetic-field components to compute transmission and reflection, including interference effects from both forward- and backward-propagating waves. This Berreman calculus is limited to infinite plane-wave solutions, but it is very useful for assessing fringes, coatings, and propagation in birefringent media. We use it extensively in our crystal-tolerance analysis and in fitting optical-coating properties. The Berreman calculus is used to calculate a Mueller matrix for an optic at some individual wavelength and incidence angle, which accounts for the interference effects within internal components such as coatings, bonding layers, or multiple stacked crystal retarders. The optic Mueller matrix can then be used in optical-propagation simulations.

