Recently, we upgraded the ViSP modulator from a stack of crystal-quartz retarders, called the ViSP PCM (Harrington and Sueoka, 2018a), to now use a custom polycarbonate three layer design (Harrington et al., 2020). We used 28 mm thickness of BK7 in two anti-reflection-coated glass windows as well as an index-matching adhesive to keep the refractive index of all components close to the nominal n=1.6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$n=1.6$\end{document}. The ViSP modulator optic is mounted behind the spectrograph entrance slit, which is an effective heat stop. Ultraviolet flux is substantially reduced from all the enhanced protected silver mirrors. We detailed this polycarbonate modulator in Harrington et al. (2020).

